Since Cosmos DB stores calendarDay as an integer (epoch milliseconds) but the search condition is in date format (yyyy-MM-dd), we need to handle this difference before querying the database.

1. Understanding the Query Field & Format Conversion
	•	Cosmos DB stores calendarDay as a long epoch timestamp (e.g., 1456704000000).
	•	API Search Conditions come as a formatted date (yyyy-MM-dd).
	•	Query must be performed on the calendarDay field, so we must convert input dates to epoch time.

Steps to Handle the Format Issue
	1.	Convert startDate and endDate from yyyy-MM-dd to epoch milliseconds in service layer before querying.
	2.	Perform the query using these epoch values against calendarDay.
	3.	Convert the results back from epoch to yyyy-MM-dd in response DTOs.

2. Updating CalendarService to Convert Dates

Convert Date to Epoch Before Querying

package com.example.calendar.service;

import com.example.calendar.dto.Calender;
import com.example.calendar.dto.CalenderSearchConditions;
import com.example.calendar.mapper.CalendarMapper;
import com.example.calendar.repository.CalendarRepository;
import lombok.RequiredArgsConstructor;
import lombok.extern.slf4j.Slf4j;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;

import java.time.LocalDate;
import java.time.ZoneId;
import java.util.List;

@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
@Slf4j
public class CalendarService {

    private final CalendarRepository calendarRepository;

    public List<Calender> searchCalendar(String requestId, CalenderSearchConditions searchConditions) {
        log.info("Processing calendar search for requestId: {}", requestId);

        searchConditions.validateDates();

        // Convert startDate and endDate from yyyy-MM-dd to epoch milliseconds
        long startEpoch = searchConditions.getStartDate() != null
                ? convertDateToEpoch(searchConditions.getStartDate())
                : 0L; // Default: Fetch from the earliest date

        long endEpoch = searchConditions.getEndDate() != null
                ? convertDateToEpoch(searchConditions.getEndDate())
                : Long.MAX_VALUE; // Default: Fetch till the latest date

        List<Calender> calendars = CalendarMapper.toDtoList(
                calendarRepository.findByDateRange(startEpoch, endEpoch)
        );

        if (calendars.isEmpty()) {
            log.warn("No calendar data found for requestId: {}", requestId);
        }

        return calendars;
    }

    private long convertDateToEpoch(LocalDate date) {
        return date.atStartOfDay(ZoneId.systemDefault()).toInstant().toEpochMilli();
    }
}

